<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-738-592  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 738 592.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 13 1990 v24 n33 p45(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Virus bill raises hopes, fears: updated laws could hold unwittingtransmitters liable for damages. (Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of1986)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A Senate bill updating the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 isbeing praised by computer and legal experts, but its passage couldencourage lawsuits against innocent institutions.andP;  The billredefines the notion of computer 'access' to cover the intentionaltransmission or distribution of unauthorized applications thatsomehow cause damage to either hardware, software or data.andO;Intentional abusers face felony charges with penalties up to fiveyears in prison and a $250,000 fine.andP;  The reckless, albeitunintentional, transmission of virus-ridden software could resultin a misdemeanor charge and up to one year in jail and a $5,000fine.andP;  The reach of the previous law would also be extended toinclude computers used in interstate communications or commerce.andO;A US Department of Justice official says the bill grantsprosecutors greater flexibility.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986 (amendments).andO;Topic:     LegislationLegal IssuesComputer virusesLiabilityUpdatingNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>